title: Access and Analyze Global Greenspace Sptatial Data
text: greenSD provides tools access analyze multi-band greenspace seasonality data cubes (available 1,028 major global cities) global land cover/NDVI data ESA WorldCover 10m Dataset. Users can download data using bounding boxes, city names, coordinates, extract values specific points, filter year seasonal time window. Moreover, package. package also supports calculating human exposure greenspace using population-weighted greenspace exposure model based Global Human Settlement Layer (GHSL) population data computing set greenspace morphology metrics patch landscape levels.

title: Access and Analyze Global Greenspace Sptatial Data
text: ðŸŒ Access global greenspace datasets bounding box, city name, geographic coordinates - Seasonal greenspace data cubes 1028 major global cities - 10m NDVI composite data ESA WorldCover ðŸ›°ï¸ Remote sensingâ€“based greenspace extraction - Automatically download process high-resolution images WorldImagery Sentinel-2 cloudless tiles (EOX) - Extract greenery map tiles - Retrieve Sentinel-2 L2A imagery compute NDVI extract raw bands ðŸ§  Multi-source land cover classification - Combine semantic segmentation remote sensing tiles land cover classification ðŸ§® Greenspace metrics calculation - Estimate population-weighted greenspace fraction (PWGF) - Calculate population-weighted greenspace exposure (PWGE) - Calculate morphological greenscape metrics (e.g., area, perimeter, shape, core area, contiguity) ðŸ“Š Visualization - Export multi-layer data animated GIFs

what: 1 Get data from Greenspace Seasonality Data Cube
title: Access and Analyze Global Greenspace Sptatial Data

title: exposure â€” compute_exposure
text: Computes population-weighted greenspace fraction human exposure greenspace based population-weighted exposure model (Chen et al., 2022), using population data Global Human Settlement Layer (GHSL; Pesaresi et al., 2024). See Details underlying method assumptions.

title: exposure â€” compute_exposure
code: compute_exposure(   r = NULL,   res = c(10, 10),   pop_year = 2020,   radius = 500,   grid_size = NULL,   height = FALSE,   pop_out = FALSE )

title: exposure â€” compute_exposure
text: r SpatRaster single/multiple greenspace layer(s), either fractional binary (non-green = 0 green = 1), typically output get_gsdc(), get_esa_wc(), get_tile_green(). res numeric vector length 2. actual spatial resolution (meters). Default c(10, 10). pop_year numeric. Year GHSL dataset use. Must one : 2015, 2020, 2025, 2030. Default 2020. radius numeric. Buffer radius (meters) used local averaging. Default 500. grid_size numeric. Optional. provided, output aggregated grid cells size (meters) returned sf object. height logical. Whether compute greenspace volume population-weighted greenspace fraction human exposure greenspace using Meta's global canopy height map (Tolan et al., 2024). (default FALSE) pop_out logical. Whether return population layer.

title: exposure â€” compute_exposure
text: SpatRaster sf. SpatRaster (grid_size NULL) layers pwgf_*, sf object columns pwge_* representing population-weighted greenspace exposure values aggregated grid polygon.

title: exposure â€” compute_exposure
text: function implements population-weighted greenspace exposure (PWGE) model: Start population raster. pixel \( \) population value \( P_i \). Create circular buffer radius \( d \) around pixel center. buffer, calculate greenspace fraction: $$G_i^d = \frac{\text{Area greenspace within buffer}}{\text{Total buffer area}}$$ Repeat \( = 1, 2, ..., N \) grid cells. Compute overall exposure: $$GE^d = \frac{\sum_i P_i \cdot G_i^d}{\sum_i P_i}$$

title: Classify land cover based on multi-source imagery datasets â€” lc_sem_seg
text: bbox sf, sfc, numeric vector (xmin, ymin, xmax, ymax) defining area interest. Optional place provided. place character vector. (optional) single line address, e.g. ("1600 Pennsylvania Ave NW, Washington") vector addresses (c("Madrid", "Barcelona")). label_year numeric. year interest: 2020 2021 retrieving land cover ESA WorldCover dataset. default 2021. tiles character vector character. One "eox" c("eox","esri") (default). tile_year numeric. year (available 2018 2024) map tiles provided EOX. zoom numeric. Zoom level map tiles. default 17. s2a character. One "all_bands", "ndvi", NULL. s2a = "all_bands", bands Sentinel-2-l2a downloaded. s2a = "ndvi", band 4 band 8 downloaded calculate NDVI train randomforest model. s2a = NULL (default), Sentinel-2-l2a included. datetime numeric vector 2. time interest c("2020-08-01", "2020-09-01") retrieving Sentinel-2-l2a images. (required, bands = "all_bands" bands = "ndvi") cloud_cover numeric. percentage cloud coverage retrieving Sentinel-2-l2a images. (required, bands = "all_bands" bands = "ndvi") vege_perc numeric. percentage cloud coverage retrieving Sentinel-2-l2a images. (required, bands = "all_bands" bands = "ndvi") sample_size numeric. total number locations sampled land cover classes. default 10000. trian_split numeric. percentage samples used training model. default 0.7. test logical. Whether test performance randomforests model. default TRUE. cores logical. Whether parallel processing used generate land cover.

title: ndvi_to_sem â€” ndvi_to_sem

title: ndvi_to_sem â€” ndvi_to_sem
text: r SpatRaster single greenspace layer, typically output get_esa_wc(), get_s2a_ndvi(). threshold numeric vector two. Thresholds, defaulting c(0.2, 0.5), classify two types vegetation areas according Hashim et al. (2019): (1) Non-vegetation (Development bare land): NDVI values generally 0.2. (2) Low vegetation (Shrub grassland): NDVI values generally 0.2 0.5. (2) High vegetation (Temperate Tropical urban forest ): NDVI values generally 0.5 1.0.

title: ndvi_to_sem â€” ndvi_to_sem
text: SpatRaster. raster, 0 represents non-green area, 1 represents shrub grassland, 2 represents trees.

title: ndvi_to_sem â€” ndvi_to_sem
text: Hashim, H., Abd Latif, Z., & Adnan, N. . (2019). Urban vegetation classification NDVI threshold value method high resolution (VHR) Pleiades imagery. International Archives Photogrammetry, Remote Sensing Spatial Information Sciences, 42, 237-240.

title: ndvi_to_sem â€” ndvi_to_sem
